Religions recommend the washing of hands for hygienic and symbolic purposes. The washing of symbolic hands, with water, but without soap, is part of the washing of ritual hands in many religions, such as bahaism, Hinduism, tevilá and netilat yadayim in Judaism, washing in Christianity and wudu in Islam. Religions also recommend washing of hygienic hands, particularly after certain actions.
Hinduism, Judaism and Islam force themselves to wash their hands after going to the bathroom.
